{"cursor":"50876","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Computer cooling' is required to remove the waste heat produced by computer\ncomponents, to keep components within permissible operating temperature limits.\n\nComponents that are susceptible to temporary malfunction or permanent failure if\noverheated include integrated circuits such as CPUs, chipset, graphics cards,\nand hard disk drives.\n\nComponents are often designed to generate as little heat as possible, and\ncomputers and operating systems may be designed to reduce power consumption\nand consequent heating according to workload, but more heat may still be\nproduced than can be removed without attention to cooling. Use of heatsinks\ncooled by airflow reduces the temperature rise produced by a given amount of\nheat. Attention to patterns of airflow can prevent the development of\nhotspots. Computer fans are very widely used to reduce temperature by actively\nexhausting hot air. There are also more exotic and extreme techniques, such as\nliquid cooling.\n\nMany computers are designed to sound an alarm or switch off if certain critical\ninternal temperatures exceed a specified limit.\n\nCooling may be designed to reduce the ambient temperature within the case of a\ncomputer e.g. by exhausting hot air, or to cool a single component or small area\n(spot cooling). Components commonly individually cooled include the CPU, GPU and\nthe northbridge chip.\n","linknr":495,"url":"Computer_cooling","recorded":1362673466,"links":58,"instances":["physics","merchandise","form_factor","computing","computing","company"],"pdf":["http://archive.computerhistory.org/resources/text/Cray/Cray.Cray2.1985.102646185.pdf","http://archive.computerhistory.org/resources/text/Cray/Cray.Cray2.1985.102646185.pdf","http://www.pnl.gov/main/publications/external/technical_reports/pnnl-19259.pdf","http://support.amd.com/us/Processor_TechDocs/23794.pdf"],"categories":["Computer hardware cooling|","Central processing unit"],"headings":["Generators of unwanted heat","Damage prevention","Mainframes and supercomputers","Air cooling","Liquid submersion cooling","Waste heat reduction","Heat-sinks","Peltier (thermoelectric) cooling","Liquid cooling","Heat pipe","Phase-change cooling","Liquid nitrogen","Liquid helium","Soft cooling","Undervolting","Optimisation of cooling","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/AMD_heatsink_and_fan.jpg/200px-AMD_heatsink_and_fan.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/ARCTIC_Accelero_Xtreme_Plus_II.JPG/200px-ARCTIC_Accelero_Xtreme_Plus_II.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Laptop_dust.jpg/200px-Laptop_dust.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d8/Chassis-plans-fan-curve.jpg/220px-Chassis-plans-fan-curve.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/f/e/8fe2914f63d77387f61e94e949f87613.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/2/b92b2fab814f1a64fc04c8c67b649cb7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/3/3/833a13f5116fcaf4bcc53320d016c32a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/4/d/34dd8c098fea5c884f9df450c1a7ec73.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Computer_case_coolingair_flow.png/200px-Computer_case_coolingair_flow.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Rs161-e2-inside.jpg/200px-Rs161-e2-inside.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/36/EBHeatsink.jpg/220px-E